Rating: 4
Was looking for a pesto recipe that called for blanching the basil to get an electric green color. This one is FANTASTIC! I blanched the basil for just over one second - literally submerged it in rapidly boiling water, then straight into the ice bath. People have mentioned spoons and tongs, but I just held onto the base of each branch. I found it important to use very fragrant basil, freshly roasted pine nuts (buy them raw, then roast them right before using), and high quality, super-stinky freshly grated Parmesan/Reggiano. I also used a bit of lemon (per earlier review) and 3/4 cup of olive oil. It was still pretty dry, so next time I will use a full cup of oil. Our pesto was PERFECTO! DELICIOUSO! MAGNIFIQUE! Bright green, bursting with flavor and a mouth-watering scent. Beautiful recipe--I will definitely use it again.

Rating: 4
Don't blanch the basil! If you do, you will lose most of the volatile oils that give it its wonderful flavour. That's the most important thing. More parmesan is good if you like a stonger-flavoured pesto, but it's not essential. Or if you're counting calories, you can use water instead of some of the oil to give a less rich but healthier result. Also, pesto freezes well for six months or so. I make big quantities in the summer when fresh basil is cheap, and freeze it in ice-cube trays so that during the winter I can just use a cube or two when I need it.

